segments.text: been one of your favorites?
Oh yes, he was one of my favorites and Chastain was another.
If we could get him, he was the history professor, and if we could get him to talking about the military campaigns of the Civil War, why
We got a lecture, a talk, and we didn't have to do anything.
He took care of it from there on.
Nevertheless, I think he was a good teacher.
And Deke Fountain in the English department, E.J.
Fermier, and
I suppose my favorite of all of them was Gilbert Allen Geist, who was a freehand drawing prof and a part of the architectural department, of course.
You mentioned if you could get Mr. Chastain talking about a battle or a Civil War campaign, then you didn't have to do anything for the class.
Did you normally have a recitation segment where
He would ask questions and you would have to answer?
He would ask questions, yes.
And he was very strict on freshmen.
There were times when we had more students in the section and there were chairs in the classroom.
in those cases where the freshmen, some of the freshmen would have to sit in the windows so that the older students could have seats, chairs.
But he was, in fact, he would ask questions in class and give you the answer himself,
King Edward had 10,000 what in his army?
Singletary?
Men.
That's right, that's right.
Such as that.
He was an entertaining sort of professor.
What were the attitudes of the students towards the administration of the school?
And I guess there was a dual administration with the president sort of in charge of academic matters and the commandant or the bull in charge of military matters.
Was it a pretty cordial relationship, or was there some conflict?
I think there was a good relationship between the two.
The students...
I generally didn't particularly like the first bull that we had there, Levi J.
Brown, and Dr. Brazell was the, well, no, Catfish Milner was the president, I believe, when I went there, and then sometime after that, Dr. Brazell came, and I believe the second year.
I recall Dr. Brazell apologizing to the students for the way he combed his hair.
He partied it in the middle, and we thought that was sort of sissy.
But Dr. Brazell was well liked, and the rest of the military instructors, most of them were pretty well liked.
Among those, I think old Sergeant Kinney was one of the best liked.
He was an old retired sergeant.
And then later on, William H.H.
Morris, who later became lieutenant general and in command of the Caribbean area during World War II, was very popular with the students.
Was he a military instructor?
Yes.
And also he was an instructor in the training camp at Leon Springs when we went in service.
There was a period in the early 20th century where on April the 1st, the entire Corps went on an extended hike to the Brazos.
Did you have that any of the years you were there?
Yes, we had a hike.
We had maneuvers for overnight.
I believe it was we had overnight camp and that sort of thing.
I don't recall whether we went to the Brazos or just where, but I do remember that we had that in our program.
Was that on April 1st?
I don't recall.
We had some pictures of a hike to the Brazos and supposedly
At one point, anyway, this was done to kind of prevent or forestall mischief on the campus on April Fool's Day.
Well, I hadn't thought of that.
I just don't recall whether it was April 1st or not.
One of the things that's of interest to us is the number of customs or traditions which have been carried on campus for a long time, such things as the bonfire and the muster and silver taps.
Were any of these in the vogue while you were there?
As I recall, silver taps was because there was one or two deaths while I was there, and I think they used
silver taps at that time.
I don't recall any of the other.
Did the entire Corps, when a boy died, if he died on campus and they carried the casket to the railroad station, did the whole Corps march with him?
No.
No, I don't believe so.
One of the students I've talked to, former students I've talked to, indicated that they did when he was there.
I see.
Perhaps it came along after or before my time.
Okay.
Did you have any girls in any classes while you were there?
No, I don't recall any girls at all in the classes.
One or two of the instructors' wives were in some of the classes.
I suppose not over a half a dozen that I recall, maybe not that many.
who were in some of the classes, but no girls at all.
Nobody who was not in some way tied to a university person or college person.
That's right.
We know that a lot of the students who went to A&M at that time had jobs of one sort or another.
Did you have any jobs on campus while you were there?
Yes.
In my freshman year, I worked nights in the agricultural building at the creamery making ice cream and cleaning up the laboratory along with another student.
He got the job and I got to work also.
Did that kind of work?
Let's see.
Was that ice cream for the cafeteria?
Or was it sold off?
I don't know what they did with it.
We packed it in 10-gallon cans, I believe it was.
And I think they shipped some of it, but I don't know.
Perhaps they did use some of it there.
And oh, I don't know.

In my senior year I did a little drawing for the building and grounds department, designed a residence for the, and drew the plans for a residence for the Commandant's dwelling which was built after I believe, after I left there.
And then we did all

during those my sophomore junior and senior years along in there we made placards for for the extension service they had a train that visited around over the state I believe at that time and they wanted signs for the various products and the usual signs that they would require then we also
kids in the architectural department.
We designed class cards for class photos or club photos.
I would say not class photos, but various club photos and made a little money that way.
We got as high as 50 cents an hour for some of that work.
The plans that you drew for the Commandant's home, you say they were actually used later?
They were used later.
Would that have been the home that Ike Ashburn?
I don't.
He was a Commandant, I believe, after that.
After, a good long while after that.
He was a Commandant after World War I, I believe.
And of course, that was before World War I that I did that work.
But the house that Ashburn lived in, and I don't know whether any other commandants lived in, I presume they did, we have had somebody in our faculty
has come into the archives looking for pictures of that house because he now owns it and lives in it.
Somebody bought it and moved it off campus.
Oh, is that right?
And he was interested in primarily the outward appearance of it.
Well, I don't remember much about it.
Well, we have some fairly small pictures that show it.
Have you?
I don't believe it's been altered any on the outside, or if it hasn't been altered very much.
I might recognize it.
I don't know.
I wasn't very good at it those days.
It's only a couple blocks off campus now.
Is that right?
I'd like to see it sometime when I'm there.
I was never aware that the house had been designed by a student.
Yes, actually, it was a frame house, just a wood frame house, wood siding, as I recall, and a porch on maybe two sides of the house.
I don't recall.
I've forgotten that.
It was located, I believe, somewhere near Guyon Hall.
I don't know.
Guyon Hall wasn't there when I was there.
It was built, I believe, in 1918.
Yes.
You had chapel in the old chapel later to be used as an armory, I believe.
Yes.
We finished a little bit early in 1917, before we left there in May, May the 3rd, I believe it was.
So you say that your class in the class of 17
What, did you kind of hurry up the last semester?
The class of 17, I believe as a unit, practically as a unit at any rate, all those who were physically able, went to a first officer's training camp at Leon Springs.
And some of the juniors also went.
For how long then did you stay in the military?
Oh, I went through that camp and competed for regular army commission and managed to get it and was assigned to a regular army regiment in Arizona and was there for about a year and back to
Camp Travis or Fort Sam Houston now, and the arms just caught us there.
And I retired then, resigned my commission in 1919, in about May.
I was in about two years, a little over, I guess.
Okay.
According to the yearbook of 1917, when you graduated for the 14-15 school year, you had been on the ZOAVI team.
Yes.
Could you tell us a little bit about that organization?
Well, you have seen on stage, in stage shows, particularly on television, fancy rifle work.
Mm-hmm.
Army, Navy, Marines.
Yes, particular drill teams.
Special drill teams, and that is what the ZOA team was.
The boy named Charlie Stoner, before he came to school, had done professional work like that.
So he organized the
that team and I believe Ronstangle might have been on it.
I'm not sure.
Was it organized in 1415?
Yes, yes.
We made, I recall, we made trips two different years with the Glee Club and the
to the various schools and towns around in Texas.
And the drill team, 13 of us went along with that.
There were actually about 17, I believe, in it, but could only use 13 on the trip.
So it was a special drill team, somewhat akin, but somewhat smaller, a good bit smaller than the Ross Volunteers.
Oh, yes.
The Ross Volunteers was just straight
company drill team.
For instance, they marched at quick time, 120 per minute, I believe.
We drilled at a much faster pace than that, and of course, there was some, I guess you'd call it a little bit of athletics along with it, special handling of the guns and so on.
Did that require a good bit of practice?
Yes, it did.
It required an awful lot of practice.
This would have been, well, although the fish drill team is a larger unit.
We didn't have a fish drill team.
No, at that time.
Was the Zouave team composed of people from all classes?
I believe so, except no seniors, as I recall.
And no freshmen.
So it would be primarily only sophomores and juniors.
Sophomores and juniors.
Do you have any idea how long that organization lasted?
I believe only as long as Charlie Stoner was there.
He was a 16-man.
He was one of my original classmates.
I recall we made two trips around over the state.
with the team.
How did you raise money for the trip or did the school supply you with some money?
No.
The school perhaps, I don't remember how we raised the money.
I suppose the school paid part of it.
At least we went by train and
What kind of uniform did you have?
We had the gray uniform.
Just a regular normal cadet uniform and have a special fancy dress.
No special uniform.
This type of organization sometimes has.
No, this was just a straight gray uniform.
I know there were a number of Civil War units with that particular title that had very fancy uniforms.
Yes, I know.
I recall.
And one year you were circulation manager of the battalion.
Right.
My roommate was business manager.
What did being circulation manager involve?
Rolling the papers in pre-addressed papers
getting them ready to mail out.
This would be to out-of-town subscribers?
Yes, yes.
Would this be, what, former students who were subscribing to the battalion?
Yes, former students who were subscribing to other schools.
Did you mail it to the advertisers?
The students would subscribe for their girlfriend, for instance, or their parents,
Someone like that.
But as far as the students were concerned, they just picked it up at a location somewhere on campus?
I don't recall about that.
I think they were just distributed by companies, perhaps.
Today, they put a pile in the library and a pile here and a pile there, and the students go by and pick them up.
Is that right?
I don't know.
Generally, they also deliver them through the whole city of College Station.
I don't know whether there was really any city of College Station when you were there.
No, there were very few people there, just the professors.
Then after you graduated, you went into the service for a while, and in 1919 you resigned your commission in the service.
What did you do then?
I went back to Clarendon, Texas, and went into the hardware and furniture business with my father and older brother.
Was that H.C. or K.C.?
H.C. H.C.
I believe the former student's directory had it as K.C., Kerbo and Sons.
No, H.C.
So it was H.C., Kerbo and Sons.
And what was, that was, did you say furniture?
Hardware and furniture.
Hardware and furniture.
And I was in there.
My father passed away in 1930, and my brother and I continued the business until 1936, when the Depression finally got us.
Then I went to work for the Department of Agriculture.
At that point, did you just close out the business?
No, we went into bankruptcy.
Went into bankruptcy.
So you went to the department?
Involuntary bankruptcy.
Then you went to the Department of Agriculture as a draftsman?
I got a job with the Department of Agriculture in Amarillo as a draftsman and then went from there as a junior architect and then as a field engineer and then as a regional architect
Dallas later on.
During that time, I was in Amarillo and San Antonio and Dallas.
And I was in Dallas when the opportunity came to come to the Veterans Administration in 46.
And I took that... Do you have any...
favorite buildings that you designed when you were with the Department of Agriculture, or did you do any designing?
Oh, I did some designing.
It was residential buildings, small residences, farm residences, and dairy barns, storm cellars.
So what would you do then?
Draw a
set of plans which they would reproduce and distribute to farmers?
Yes, it would become a standard plan then and they would send it out to the various counties as they needed and the writing of specifications of course and so on.
So then you came to Lubbock at the Veterans Administration in 46.
In 46, in the latter part of 46, as Assistant Chief Appraiser.
In 47, I became Chief Appraiser.
What was your responsibility then?
Well, we had 79 counties of the western counties of the state

we did devalue our supervised evaluation and the construction of VA housing in those counties of course not personally and but through uh through uh designated inspectors and appraisers in the various counties like in El Paso and in Amarillo
Would this be if a veteran wanted to borrow money to buy a house, then your office would appraise, you would have someone who would appraise the...
Yes, for instance, some company would submit an application for appraisal of a house in El Paso.
We would send it to, say, Jay Weems in El Paso.
he would send his appraisal in, we would review it and issue a evaluation on it.
And then if it had to be built, while we had inspectors in El Paso, we would designate him to do the inspecting during the construction.
And I was with that until
1965, a short time before the, well, on my 70th birthday, well, I had to retire, of course, mandatory retirement.
And since then, you've been a self-employed appraiser?
Since then, I've had more fun appraising than I ever had before.
I work kind of when I want to, and I try not to do too much, but enough to stay busy.
Uh-huh.
It gives you a good bit more freedom than you've had in the past.

Oh, yes, I work when I want to, and I punch no clocks, and if I don't want an assignment, if someone wants an appraisal made and I don't want to do it, it's easy to... Do you work only in Lubbock, or do you go outside of Lubbock?
Oh, surrounding towns on occasion, but most practically all together in Lubbock and practically all together in residential work.
All residential housing...
This would be, you would be working as an appraiser for a bank contemplating loaning money to buy a house or?
Not as an employee of that bank.
No, I mean you're consulting appraisers.
Right, I'm an independent appraiser in other words, and I do appraisal work for, not only for the savings loans and banks and so on, locally, but...
There is a company in Wisconsin who reinsures or insures a portion of local loans.
Occasionally they want a spot check made to see that those things are in line, and I do work for them.
Also, companies like Texas Instrument
Eastman Kodak and so on want to move an employee, they assist him and I do appraisals for them to establish market value.
They then in turn buy his house?
They handle the deal for him.
Do you have any other activities in which you participate?
No, I really don't.
Have you become involved in Lubbock politics or anything like that?
Oh, no, no.
I have my druthers, of course, about politics, but I don't take no active interest in it.
